ifc sign deal to expand insurance to farmer in east africa
nairobi , nov. 25 ( xinhua ) -- international finance corporation ( ifc ) have sign agreement with three partner to expand access to insurance to thousand of farmer and livestock herders in kenya and rwanda to help protect their crop , animal and livelihood from weather @-@ related risk and natural disaster .
ifc , through the global index insurance facility ( giif ) , will confer grant totaling roughly 4.1 million u . s . dollar to the syngenta foundation for sustainable agriculture @/@ uap insurance weather index insurance initiative in kenya ; the international livestock research institute ( ilri ) livestock index insurance project in northern kenya ; and the microensure weather index insurance project in rwanda .
" these partnership highlight ifc 's commitment to expand insurance and other financial product where they be need most in africa .
the global index insurance facility will facilitate farmer ' access to credit , lead to increase productivity , improve livelihood and greater food security , " jean philippe prosper , ifc director for eastern and southern africa say .
" we be grateful to the donor that have generously provide fund and to our partner for support this program ."
the grant , the first three provide under the giif program , will help bring weather @-@ relate , index @-@ based insurance to about 35 , 000 farmer and 5,000 livestock herders in east africa over the next three year .
" the implementation of these three first giif project in kenya and rwanda will support the development of new insurance product and will increase expertise in this field , which will benefit smallholder and livestock keeper affect by climatic event , " he say .
" in addition to the giif , the european union be provide further finance to the ilri livestock insurance project in kenya through the 10 th european development fund , kenya rural development project that will start in 2011."
ifc will confer a grant of up to 2.4 million dollar on syngenta foundation for sustainable agriculture , which expect to help insure 20,000 farmer in kenya over the next three year
ifc will confer a grant of up to 154,000 dollar on the ilri , which expect to help insure 5,000 livestock herders in northern kenya over the next two year .
ifc will confer a grant of up to 1.6 million dollar on microensure , which expect to insure 15,000 farmer in rwanda over the next three year .
ifc 's giif program be establish in 2009 to assist the development of index @-@ based insurance for natural disaster and weather risk in develop country , where insurance be rarely available .
the grant will fund advisory activity , include local capacity build , infrastructure development , product development , and development of local insurance company ' capacity to provide index @-@ based insurance product .
index @-@ based insurance insure against catastrophic event , such as wind storm or drought , depending on their severity .
index @-@ link insurance product eliminate the need for insurance company to individually verify claim , reduce transaction cost and make it easier for the product and service to be offer to rural community and in frontier region .
the european union commit 24.5 million euros as the first donor to the giif trust fund .
the fund be also support by japan 's ministry of finance with an initial grant of 2 million dollar , and the dutch ministry of foreign affair , which provide fund to establish the facility .
